            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Chloe Miller is a product of the Bay Area\u2019s unique fusion of technology and culture. Raised in San Jose by her Korean-born graphic designer mother and her white, American software engineer father, Chloe\u2019s childhood was a blend of digital logic and analog artistry. Her parents\u2019 dinner table conversations often volleyed between code and color theory, planting the seeds for her fascination with the intersection of human behavior and design. This led her to pursue a Cognitive Science degree at UC Davis, where she became engrossed in understanding the \u201cwhy\u201d behind human choices.\n\nHer career began at a small, ambitious startup in San Francisco. The venture burned bright and fast, ultimately failing within two years. While professionally disappointing, the experience was a profound turning point. Witnessing the team's passion and the users' frustration firsthand taught her a lesson no textbook could: empathy is the most critical component of innovation. This hard-won insight made her a highly sought-after UX Researcher. Today, she works at a large tech firm, translating complex user data into intuitive, human-centric product designs.\n\nChloe\u2019s life is anchored in her Hayes Valley apartment, a sanctuary of clean lines and warm, natural textures. Her days begin with a pour-over coffee before she catches the company shuttle for the 4.5-mile commute to her SoMa office. She values this liminal time, using it to listen to podcasts on psychology or urban planning. Evenings are for connection: cooking with her boyfriend, Leo, a landscape architect who keeps her grounded and away from tech-talk; enjoying cocktails with a tight-knit circle of friends at a nearby bar; or attending a weekly pottery class, a tactile hobby that connects her to her mother\u2019s artistic roots.\n\nThough comfortable and successful, Chloe aspires to more. The memory of her first startup's failure instilled in her a desire for purpose-driven work. Her long-term dream is to lead a UX research team for a company focused on mental health technology or digital accessibility, applying her expertise not just to create seamless products, but to build more compassionate and supportive digital spaces."
